[[File:Alcatraz wharf2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Alcatraz wharf]] '''Alcatraz Wharf''' is located on the southeast side of [[Alcatraz Island]], in [[San Francisco Bay]], [[California]], US. Classified as building number 33 of the Alcatraz Island National Historic Landmark, its historic name variants were "Alcatraz Dock" and "Alcatraz Pier". It is the main access point to Alcatraz. Another dock on the island's northwest side was only used for rock loading.<ref name="nps.gov/goga">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:8g1Y2I7Xg_0J:www.nps.gov/goga/historyculture/upload/Physical%2520History%2520Part%25202.pdf+&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShs1gH-ylMIdi-F5i_R9BtJaDSeH9LKjtOlcpczJoV7lTWs9Cv3aDVhC5adEKPKlfBey_eZmFyqPxDF1RplR9tnXdQZlzN6GhUpOgDjJgUyHKfgWWfJJY8h1SJZR5LMyDP3SOAy&sig=AHIEtbRaYY9PKSDsUHf0s8qph6kKJ9shOg&pli=1|title=Alcatraz Island - Golden Gate National Recreation Area|publisher=National Park Service|pages=1|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref> The wharf contained many of the islands historic buildings, including [[Building 64]] (Alcatraz Defensive Barracks), the Bombproof Barracks, Chinatown, Ranger Office, Garage, Dock Tower, Storage Vault, and Firebox #3.<ref name="nps.gov">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:9u75zYJbcmwJ:www.nps.gov/goga/historyculture/upload/Ch-8-Alcatraz-CLR-Appendix.pdf+&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESg6AJsF1P7GjCFjwI3FoRjuHZmLE7OYiCeD-IYvMfO5RICa2r3movb1LPYWgjqDPJ20y_MpmW4yJs_rfpQCVVQJv5RQnl3yQTL6081pr6MjFusqqJFVScnOR1PQhek-HVMPkN-x&sig=AHIEtbTK8yJWcVa8V5WJPvyFyVcrXCiAHA|title=Appendix 1. Historic Names for Alcatraz Island Features by Character Area|work=Alcatraz Island National Historic Landmark - Cultural Landscape Report|publisher=National Park Services|pages=5|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref>
==History== {{Quote box | quote ="From the moment a convict sets foot on the Alcatraz wharf, he has, according to the guards, one consuming thought: how to get off." (J. Campbell Bruce, ''Escape from Alcatraz'') | source =<ref name="Watson2012">{{cite book|last=Watson|first=Stephanie|title=The Escape from Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dw-4z4Cmb8MC&pg=PA9|accessdate=10 September 2012|date=1 January 2012|publisher=ABDO|isbn=978-1-61783-303-8|pages=9–}}</ref> | width =25% | align =right }}
The wharf, or boat dock, was established on Alcatraz in the 1850s to permit the landing of men and building materials to construct [[Alcatraz Citadel|a fort]], completed in 1859. In 1867, the ''[[General McPherson (ship)|General McPherson]]'' was built to serve the island and other military institutions in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]], as Alcatraz became a long-term military prison from 1868. The steamer towed officers, prisoners and food and water supplies to island between 1867 and 1886, landing at the dock twice daily before being replaced.<ref name="FanningWong2007">{{cite book|last1=Fanning|first1=Branwell|last2=Wong|first2=William|title=Angel Island|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GJW2150AQzYC&pg=PA28|accessdate=5 September 2012|date=4 April 2007|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-4719-0|page=28}}</ref> [[File:Alcatraz wharf.jpg|thumb|left]] During the time as a [[Alcatraz Federal Penitentiary|federal penitentiary]], a prisoner once attempted to escape on a boat from the boat by dressing as an officer. The Sally Port led from the dock to the original citadel on Alcatraz along a walkway, 12&nbsp;ft above a dry moat. Today the dock meets visitors to the museum on the island and is served by boat trips daily. [[Building 64]] lies in front of the dock, built in 1905.
In the mid-1880s, work on the wharf area was undertaken to repair it and to create coals sheds and a boathouse.<ref name="nps.gov/goga" /> The [[Alcatraz Citadel]]'s saltwater engine house was located on the wharf.<ref name="alcatrazhistory.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.alcatrazhistory.com/rock/rock-019.htm|title=Garrison Life on the Rock, 1859-1934 |work=alcatrazhistory.com|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref> The oil steamer "Rosecrans," owned by the [[Associated Oil Company]], was destroyed by fire above the water line and sank in deep water off the wharf in the early 1910s. Her crew of forty-two men escaped by jumping into the bay and swimming ashore.<ref name="VanNess1912">{{cite book|title=Paint, oil and drug review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LwRZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174|accessdate=10 September 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1912|publisher=D. Van Ness Pub. Co..|pages=174–}}</ref>
Seismic rehabilitation of the wharf occurred in the early 2000s. The retrofit to the existing wharf and its facilities consisted of concrete demolition, excavation, and installation of tiebacks. Reinforced steel and concrete were added to a new deck. Work was also done on the deteriorated piles under the wharf deck.<ref name="wattsconstructors.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.wattsconstructors.com/viewproject.jsp?id=2&index=0|title=Alcatraz Wharf Seismic Rehabilitation, Alcatraz Island, San Francisco, California|date=2007|publisher=Watts Constructors|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref>David Finney is the youngest person to swim the South End Rowing Club Alcatraz Swim when he swam it in 2015 at ten years old.
