[[File:Boston archives building 002.jpg|thumb|right|Boston City Archives building in West Roxbury, MA.]] The '''Boston City Archives''' are located in [[West Roxbury, Massachusetts|West Roxbury]], MA, and are the repository for all official records that must be kept to honor both the history of the municipal government in [[Boston]] and the legal rights of its citizens.<ref name=home>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/archivesandrecords/default.asp |title=Archives and Records - City of Boston |format= |work= |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> The City Archives were established in 1988.<ref name=act>{{cite web |url=http://archives.lib.state.ma.us/actsResolves/1988/1988Acts0068.pdf |title=archives.lib.state.ma.us - Acts 1968 - Chapter 68 |format= |work= |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> The collection was originally housed in an old school building in Hyde Park, until the importance of preserving the expanding number of records became a focus of attention.<ref name=Globe>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/121667785.html?FMT=ABS&date=May%2025,%202002 |title=City's historic archives still seek a worthy home |format= |work=[[Boston Globe]] Archive |accessdate=2010-03-31|author=Sarah Schweitzer|date=2005-05-25}}</ref><ref name=Tobin>{{cite web |url=http://mblc.state.ma.us/hypermail-archives/semls/0205/1901.php |title=Tobin files order for hearing on permanent home for city archives |format= |work=Massachusetts Board of Library Commissioners |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref><ref name=Globe-2>{{cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2005/02/27/this_city_has_real_baggage_and_soon_a_place_to_put_it/ |title=This city has real baggage, and soon a place to put it |format= |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |author=Johny Diaz |date=2005-02-27 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>
== Collections == The City Archives holds records for over 60 current and historic government entities and departments. The bulk of these records consist of documentation of the history of Boston since incorporation as a city in 1822, although some records go back to the early 17th century. It is only recently that many city departments have begun to give their records to the archives, so the collection is constantly growing. This is aided by the movement of the collections to the new facility in West Roxbury. Prior to this move, the [[Heritage Health Index Report]] had found that the resources and facilities at the Hyde Park facilities had been lacking.<ref name="heritage">{{cite web |url=http://www.heritagepreservation.org/HHI/HHIsummary.pdf |title=The Heritage Health Index Report on the State of America’s Collections |format= |work=www.heritagepreservation.org |accessdate=2010-03-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923094720/http://heritagepreservation.org/HHI/HHIsummary.pdf# |archive-date=2010-09-23 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
Most notably, the collections include: * Records relating to [[immigration]] and poverty at the time of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Irish Famine]] * Documentation of Boston’s role in the [[American Civil War]] * Boston Public Schools Desegregation-Era Records (assisted by a grant from the NHPRC and the city's largest department, [[Boston Public Schools]])<ref name=NEA>{{cite journal |url=http://www.newenglandarchivists.org/pdfs/NEA_Newsletter_October2007.pdf |title=From Hemenway to Rivermoor: Relocating the Boston City Archives |author=John J. McColgan |date=October 2007 |format= |work=New England Archivists Newsletter |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=4–6 |accessdate=2010-03-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125181417/http://newenglandarchivists.org/pdfs/NEA_Newsletter_October2007.pdf |archivedate=2010-11-25 |df= }}</ref> * City Council Records * Transit Department Records * City Tax and Treasury Records
