{{Infobox court case | name = Cavanaugh v. Ulster Weaving Ltd | court = | date_filed = | image = | date decided = | full name = | citations = | judges = [[Viscount Simonds]], [[Lord Tucker]], [[Lord Keith of Avonholm]], [[Lord Somervell of Harrow]] and [[Lord Jenkins]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = | Keywords = }}
{{italic title}} '''''Cavanaugh v. Ulster Weaving Ltd.''''', (1960) A.C. 145 and A.C. (1959) 2 All E.R. (H.L.) is a [[legal judgment]] in a [[tort]] case decided by the Judicial Committee of the [[House of Lords]], clarifying the test for [[negligence]] by finding that [[evidence]] of trade practices is insufficient to prove absence of negligence of employer's duties on the facts.<ref> {{cite book |year=2009 |editor1-last=Blom-Cooper |editor1-first=Louis Jacques |editor2-last=Dickson |editor2-first=Brice |editor3-last=Drewry |editor3-first=Gavin |title=The Judicial House of Lords: 1876-2009 |url=https://openlibrary.org/works/OL16593586W/The_Judicial_House_of_Lords_1876-2009 |location=Oxford, UK |publisher=Oxford University Press |publication-date=13 Aug 2009 |page=311 |isbn=9780199532711 |ref=Blom-Cooper et al. }}</ref>
An employer's duty towards its employees was expressed by [[Donald Somervell, Baron Somervell of Harrow|Lord Somervell of Harrow]] as follows: "put in its simplest terms the general scope of the duty of an employer is a duty to take reasonable care in all circumstances."<ref> {{cite journal | last = Frank | first = W. F.
| date = June 1064 | title = The Safety Provisions in British Factory Law | url = http://digitalcommons.law.lsu.edu/lalrev/vol24/iss4/6 | journal = Louisiana Law Review | publisher = LSU Law enter | volume = 24 | issue = 4 | pages = 784 | doi = | accessdate = 16 Dec 2013 }}</ref>
